Chapter 2 – Part 1: Using Templates in Flask

In Chapter 1, our route returned simple text:
      return 'My First Flask Page'

Now we improve it.
Instead of returning plain text, we return an HTML page.

# Step 1 — Create Templates Folder
Inside learnFlaskApp/, we created a new folder:

learnFlaskApp/
│
├── __init__.py
├── routes.py
└── templates/
    └── index.html

Important: 
The folder must be named exactly: templates
Flask automatically looks for HTML files inside a folder named templates.

# Step 2 — Create index.html
Inside the templates folder, we created: index.html

Example content:

      <!DOCTYPE html>
      <html>
      <head>
          <title>Flask Page</title>
      </head>
      <body>
          <h1>This is Flask index page</h1>
      </body>
      </html>

This is a normal HTML file.
There is nothing Flask-specific here yet.

# Step 3 — Modify routes.py

Before:

      @app.route('/')
      def index():
          return 'My First Flask Page'
      
      Now we import render_template:
      
      from flask import render_template

And modify the route:

      @app.route('/')
      def index():
          return render_template('index.html')

What is render_template()?
render_template() is a Flask function that:
• Looks inside the templates folder
• Finds the HTML file
• Processes it
• Sends it to the browser

So when someone visits:
      http://127.0.0.1:5000/

Flask:
      Calls index()

Executes render_template('index.html')
Loads the file from templates/index.html
Sends the full HTML page to the browser

Execution Flow Now
Browser → '/' route
        ↓
index() function
        ↓
render_template('index.html')
        ↓
Load file from templates/
        ↓
Send HTML to browser

Why We Use Templates
Returning plain text is fine for testing, but real websites use:
• HTML
• CSS
• JavaScript

Templates allow us to:
• Build real web pages
• Add design
• Add layout
• Later pass dynamic data

This is the first step toward real web development.

Important Rule
Flask automatically searches for:
project_name/templates/
If you rename the folder (like template or html), Flask will not find your files unless you configure it manually.

Mental Model
Old Way            New Way
Return plain text  Return full HTML page
Simple response    Real webpage
return 'text'      return render_template('file.html')

